description: MAD Magazine has been a staple of American pop culture since the first issue in 1952. MAD was initially published by EC Comics (now published by DC Comics) and started out as a comic satirizing other comics but became a magazine when the comics code was created because the limits were looser. MAD Magazine has been seen in movies like the 1966 film Fahrenheit 451 and TV Shows like The Simpsons and even spawned its own programming, such as the live action MAD TV on FOX and the animated MAD! on Cartoon Network. MAD continues to satirize comics, but has branched out into making fun of pretty much everything, from television to books to film to advertising on tv and Spy vs Spy in Mountain Dew Ads.
name: MAD

description: There are few people in our lives who have as much influence on us as our mother and father, brothers and sisters. Family ties are the earliest ties that bind, setting the tone for the paths we will take in our future. So what if your father is Dirk Hopeless and your mother Nikki Savage, a superstar couple from the days of punk rock? When you're born a rebel, what can you possibly do to make yourself stand apart? For Rat Hopeless-Savage, the answer is to leave home and start a new life somewhere, become a normal citizen with a nine-to-five job. It's going pretty well, too, until Dirk and Nikki are kidnapped, and suddenly the family Rat tried so hard to deny needs him more than ever. His siblings -- sisters Arsenal and Zero, and brother Twitch -- know the Rat of old is the only one who can find their parents, and they're determined to make him trade his white-washed existence for the leather jacket and spiked hair of his youth. What follows is a madcap race against the clock, and a hilarious look at what happens when alternative lifestyles become the norm.
name: Hopeless Savages

description:
It's the return of everyone's favorite hormone-crazed comic book teenagers. Bleu Finnegan and the gang are back for another hilarious round of adolescent warfare. The battle begins when Alan and Victor engage in their deranged idea of a courtship ritual - videotaping Bleu while she's taking a bath! What follows is an all-out nuclear holocaust, as the girls make it their mission to retrieve the tape and restore Bleu's devastated reputation. Unfortunately, the damage may already be done. Bleu is convinced Mr. Bishop, the teacher who is her most pronounced crush, thinks she's a slut, and she begins to be haunted by a mischievous pooka spirit who's taken the form of a giant, talking otter. Worse still, now the boys are fighting for her affection - thanks to Erin getting involved and stirring up their emotions. With the odds stacked against her, can Bleu find a way to get the contraband video out of Alan's sweaty hands and still walk with her head held high?

  • Blue Monday: Absolute Beginners
name: Blue Monday: Absolute Beginners

description:
The Red Star is a Sci-Fi / Fantasy comic based in a country highly analogous culturally and geographically to the Soviet Union in the latter half of the twentieth century. "The United Republics of the Red Star" occupy a similar place on the world map as the real life U.S.S.R.. Their enemy at the beginning of the story, Al'Istaan, occupies the same approximate area as Afghanistan. The military uniforms are similar, many of the character names are Russian in origin, and some of the mystical elements have their roots in Russian lore.

The military forces of the U.R.R.S. have fully incorporated magic into their arsenal of weapons, providing power sources, energy beams of massive power, shields, and teleportational gates among other effects. Sorcerers, called "Warkasters", have their own corps within the command structure, though they are usually integrated with either aircraft or infantry troops when going into battle. Spells, called "protocols", are "kast" with extreme military precision.

The source of this magical energy has been revealed to be P.H.E. "Post Human Energy", the energy generated by the enslaved souls of all humans that have died before. The crew of the Skyfurnace R.S.S. Konstantinov have mutinied and gone into the spirit realm in order to lay siege to the fortress of the "Imprisoned Afterlife".

Despite it being one continuous story, The Red Star is in its third "Book" or incarnation. The first nine issues (2000), plus intermediary stories, were published by Image comics. For the second volume (2003), the first three issues were published by Archangel Studios in conjuction with CGE/CrossGen Comics. The last two issues of volume two as well as the third book/volume (2006), Sword of Lies, are published by Archangel Studios alone.

Collected Editions

  • The Red Star: The Battle Of Kar Dathra's Gate (#1-4)
  • The Red Star: Treasury Edition (#1-4, #6-9)
  • The Red Star: Deluxe Edition Volume 1 (#1-4, #6-9)

description:
Collected in The Filth.

Even by writer Grant Morrison's standards, "The Filth" was wonderfully strange. With artwork by Chris Weston and Gary Erskine, It followed the adventures of Officer Slade, an agent for an inter-reality agency known as the Hand. The first issue showed Slade hiding out from the Hand in a para-personality of Greg Freely, only to be tracked down by ex-colleague Nil and forced to return to duty. With highly designed covers by Segura Inc., "The Filth" pushed the boundaries of storytelling.
name: The Filth

description: Writer / artist Sam Keith's work had always been slightly edgier than most, even when working on mainstream books. This was especially true on "Four Women." Published by Homage, "Four Women" was a tough thriller about sexual assault and survivor guilt. The story was told in flashback as Donna gave her psychiatrist details of a vicious attack that had happened while she was on her way to a wedding with three female friends. Sam Keith's realistic story made the horrific acts even more disturbing.
name: Four Women

A series focusing on the next generation of young heroes. The entire run was written by Peter David and mostly drawn by Todd Nauck. The series focused on a core team of Robin (Tim Drake), Superboy (Kon-El), Impulse, and Wonder Girl (Cassandra Sandsmark) with the Red Tornado as their mentor. Other established heroes such as Arrowette, The Ray, and Lobo (who was de-aged at the time) would drift in and out of the team, while Empress and Secret were created for the series.

Due to three of the team's core members having their own solo titles running simultaneously with this series, events in Young Justice are often affected by/reflected in Impulse vol. 1, Superboy vol. 4, and Robin vol. 4.

description:
The first series for the Max-comics imprint series from Marvel Comics. Alias is a comic book series created by writer Brian Michael Bendis and artist Michael Gaydos. The series follows Jessica Jones, owner of Alias Investigations and former costumed superhero named Jewel. The 28 issues chronicle Jessica's many cases concerning the super powered community while exploring the aspects of her past and personality that drove her to abandon her life as a superhero. After issue 28, the series was continued in The Pulse.

Collected Editions

  • Jessica Jones: Alias Vol. 1 (#1-9)
  • Vol. 2: Come Home (#11-15)
  • Jessica Jones: Alias Vol. 2 (#11-15)
  • Vol. 3: Underneath (#10, 16-21)
  • Jessica Jones: Alias Vol. 3 (#10 & 16-21)
  • Vol. 4: Secret Origin of Jessica Jones (#22-28)
  • Hardcover (#1-9)
  • Ultimate Collection Vol. 1 (#1-15)
  • Ultimate Collection Vol. 2 (#16-28)
  • Omnibus (#1-28)

description:
This miniseries introduces Elsa Bloodstone, a teenage girl who never met her father, the long-lived monster Hunter Bloodstone, but inherits his weapons, wealth, legacy and mystical bloodstone artifact.
Accompanied by her late father's Frankenstein-like housekeeper Adam, Elsa learns monster hunting on a steep learning curve, encountering Dracula, The Living Mummy and more.
 
The series is written with a strong humorous bent, and was likely intended as somewhat of a cash-in on the popularity of Buffy the Vampire Slayer at the time.
After this miniseries, the character went dormant for 4 years or so until she was dusted off and largely reinvented from scratch as a member of Warren Ellis' Nextwave.
name: Bloodstone
